[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there a standard reference for the following fact:<br>\nLet <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> be a small category and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> a set of colimit cocones in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>; then the category of presheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> which take the cocones of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> to limit cones is the free cocompletion of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> subject to the condition that the colimit cones of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> are preserved.</p>",
        "id": 218905737,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1607125685
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Preferably a reference where understanding the statement of the theorem is easier than proving it yourself. I'm looking at you <em>Basic Concepts of Enriched Category Theory</em>...)</p>",
        "id": 218905763,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1607125729
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You haven't seen nothing yet - wait 'til <em>Advanced Concepts of Enriched Category Theory</em> comes out.  <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span></p>",
        "id": 218910921,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1607131749
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The standard reference is Theorem 6.23 of <em>Basic concepts</em>, but a more approachable reference may be Velebil–Adámek's <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022404901000512\">A remark on conservative cocompletions of categories</a>, which at least sketches the proof.</p>",
        "id": 218916396,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1607140642
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(I moved John's comment, because it seemed clearly in reply to this topic.)</p>",
        "id": 218916498,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1607140802
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think neither of these sources really contains the exact statement above, because they both construct the cocompletion by some kind of transfinite construction (e.g., closure under colimits), which is necessary if you want to adjoin only certain types of colimits. In this special case of a small category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> and adjoining <em>all</em> colimits, there's this direct description of the cocompletion, and it takes more work to extract this description from the general construction (which is not hard, but then it is not a hard theorem to begin with).</p>",
        "id": 218935053,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1607174641
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I came across <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/349409/universal-property-of-the-cocomplete-category-of-models-of-a-limit-sketch\">https://mathoverflow.net/questions/349409/universal-property-of-the-cocomplete-category-of-models-of-a-limit-sketch</a>,<br>\nand thereby Theorem 2.2.4 of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1105.3104.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/1105.3104.pdf</a>, which might be the best reference.</p>",
        "id": 218935144,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1607174763
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, that's true. In that case, a reference is Proposition 11.4 and Theorem 11.5 of Fiore's <em>Enrichment and Representation Theorems for Categories of Domains and Continuous Functions</em>.</p>",
        "id": 218939299,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1607181792
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Perfect, thanks!</p>",
        "id": 218984978,
